---
import DocsPage from "../../layouts/DocsPage.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../../components/CodeBlock.astro";
---

<DocsPage title="Getting Started">
  <h1 class="indent">Getting Started with Le-Kit</h1>
  <p>
    This guide will help you to get started with using Le-Kit in your projects.
    It covers the installation process, the basic usage of the library, and some
    tips and best practices to make the most out of it.
  </p>

  <h2 class="indent">
    <a href="#installation" id="installation">Installation</a>
  </h2>
  <p>To install Le-Kit, you can use npm or yarn:</p>

  <le-tabs class="code-tabs" value="npm">
    <le-tab-panel label="npm" value="npm">
      <CodeBlock language="bash" code={`npm install le-kit`} />
    </le-tab-panel>
    <le-tab-panel label="yarn" value="yarn">
      <CodeBlock language="bash" code={`yarn add le-kit`} />
    </le-tab-panel>
    <le-tab-panel label="pnpm" value="pnpm">
      <CodeBlock language="bash" code={`pnpm add le-kit`} />
    </le-tab-panel>
  </le-tabs>

  <h2 class="indent">
    <a href="#usage" id="usage">Basic Usage</a>
  </h2>
  <p>
    After installing Le-Kit, you should register the custom elements in your
    project. You can do this by importing the library in your main JavaScript or
    TypeScript file:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    language="jsx"
    code={`import { defineCustomElements } from 'le-kit/loader';

(async () => {
   defineCustomElements();
})();
`}
  />

  <p>
    Once you have registered the custom elements, you can start using them in
    your HTML. For example, to use the <code>&lt;le-button&gt;</code> component, you
    can simply add it to your HTML like this:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    language="html"
    code={`<le-button variant="primary">Click me</le-button>`}
  />

  <h2 class="indent">
    <a href="#frameworks" id="frameworks">Frameworks Integration</a>
  </h2>
  <p>
    In case if you are using a framework like React, Vue, or Angular, you might
    need to follow additional steps to integrate Le-Kit components properly.
    They will be described here, when we're sure they are working correctly.
  </p>

  <h2 class="indent">
    <a href="#tips" id="tips">Tips and Best Practices</a>
  </h2>
  <p>Here are some tips to help you get the most out of Le-Kit:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Always check the <a href="/components">documentation for each component</a
      > to understand its props and how to use it effectively.
    </li>
    <li>
      Use the <a href="/docs/theming">theming capabilities</a> of Le-Kit to customize
      the look and feel of your application.
    </li>
    <li>
      Don't hesitate to <a href="/docs/contributing">contribute</a> to the library
      if you have ideas for new components or improvements!
    </li>
  </ul>
</DocsPage>
